'''Susuki Mizu Shrine''' (й Ҳй ҲеІҗж°ҙзҘһзӨҫ) is a [[Shinto shrine]] located in [[Chikuma City]], [[Nagano Prefecture]]. It is identified as the {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|ејҸеӨ–зӨҫ|1=Shikigeisha|12=draft|12=draft}} Susuki Mizu Shrine, with its {{ill|Modern typeing System|ja|иҝ‘д»ЈзӨҫж јеҲ¶еәҰ|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|12=draft|12=draft}} classification as a former {{ill|GЕҚsha|ja|йғ·зӨҫ|12=draft|12=draft}}.

== Overview ==

According to shrine tradition, it was founded in the second year of the [[HakuhЕҚ era]] (673 CE). Initially known as {{ill|HЕҚri Shrine|ja|зҘқзҘһзӨҫ|12=draft|12=draft}}, it later enshrined {{ill|SannЕҚ Gongen|ja|еұұзҺӢжЁ©зҸҫ|12=draft|12=draft}} from {{ill|Hie Shrine|ja|ж—ҘеҗүеӨ§зӨҫ|12=draft|12=draft}} at the behest of {{ill|Kanasashi Toneri Masanaga|ja|йҮ‘еҲәиҲҺдәәжӯЈй•·|12=draft|12=draft}}, a {{ill|Gunji|ja|йғЎеҸё|12=draft|12=draft}} of {{ill|Hanishina District|ja|еҹҙз§‘йғЎ|12=draft|12=draft}}, after flooding from the {{ill|Chikuma River|ja|еҚғжӣІе·қ|12=draft|12=draft}} during the {{ill|JЕҚgan era|ja|иІһиҰі|12=draft|12=draft}}. In later periods, it gained the patronage of the {{ill|Sanada clan|ja|зңҹз”°ж°Ҹ|12=draft|12=draft}}, receiving land grants of 300 koku and festival contributions. 

Rebuilt in 1851 during the {{ill|Kaei era|ja|еҳүж°ё|12=draft|12=draft}} under the guidance of {{ill|Tatekawa WashirЕҚ Tomimasa|ja|з«Ӣе·қе’ҢеӣӣйғҺеҜҢжҳҢ|12=draft|12=draft}}, the shrine was renamed from "SannЕҚ Daigongen Palace" to "Susuki Mizu Shrine" by the {{ill|Yoshida clan|ja|еҗүз”°е®¶|12=draft|12=draft}} in 1781 ({{ill|Tenmei|ja|еӨ©жҳҺ|12=draft|12=draft}} 1). The shrine formerly held rituals involving the exchange of {{ill|Mikoshi|ja|зҘһијҝ|12=draft|12=draft}} with {{ill|Amamiya Shrine|ja|йӣЁе®®гҒ®еқҗж—ҘеҗүзҘһзӨҫ|12=draft|12=draft}} but discontinued this in 1872 (Meiji 5).

The shrine grounds span approximately 27 ken (east to west) and 34 ken (north to south). Revered as a {{ill|Water deity|ja|ж°ҙзҘһ|1=Suijin|lt=water god|12=draft|12=draft}}, it has long served as the guardian deity of the Yashiro Irrigation Weir.

