'''Susuki Mizu Shrine''' (й Ҳй ҲеІҗж°ҙзҘһзӨҫ) is a [[Shinto shrine]] located in [[Chikuma City]], [[Nagano Prefecture]]. It is identified as the {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|ејҸеӨ–зӨҫ|1=Shikigeisha|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikinaisha|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikigeisha|qq=}} Susuki Mizu Shrine, with its {{ill|Modern typeing System|ja|иҝ‘д»ЈзӨҫж јеҲ¶еәҰ|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|1=Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Modern typeing System|13=User:Immanuelle/Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|qq=}} classification as a former {{ill|GЕҚsha|ja|йғ·зӨҫ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/GЕҚsha|qq=}}.

== Overview ==

According to shrine tradition, it was founded in the second year of the [[HakuhЕҚ era]] (673 CE). Initially known as {{ill|HЕҚri Shrine|ja|зҘқзҘһзӨҫ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/HЕҚri Shrine|qq=}}, it later enshrined {{ill|SannЕҚ Gongen|ja|еұұзҺӢжЁ©зҸҫ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/SannЕҚ Gongen|qq=}} from {{ill|Hie Shrine|ja|ж—ҘеҗүеӨ§зӨҫ|1=Hiyoshi Taisha|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hie Shrine|13=User:Immanuelle/Hiyoshi Taisha|qq=}} at the behest of {{ill|Kanasashi Toneri Masanaga|ja|йҮ‘еҲәиҲҺдәәжӯЈй•·|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanasashi Toneri Masanaga|qq=}}, a {{ill|Gunji|ja|йғЎеҸё|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gunji|qq=}} of {{ill|Hanishina District|ja|еҹҙз§‘йғЎ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hanishina District|qq=}}, after flooding from the {{ill|Chikuma River|ja|еҚғжӣІе·қ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chikuma River|qq=}} during the {{ill|JЕҚgan era|ja|иІһиҰі|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/JЕҚgan era|qq=}}. In later periods, it gained the patronage of the {{ill|Sanada clan|ja|зңҹз”°ж°Ҹ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sanada clan|qq=}}, receiving land grants of 300 koku and festival contributions. 

Rebuilt in 1851 during the {{ill|Kaei era|ja|еҳүж°ё|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kaei era|qq=}} under the guidance of {{ill|Tatekawa WashirЕҚ Tomimasa|ja|з«Ӣе·қе’ҢеӣӣйғҺеҜҢжҳҢ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tatekawa WashirЕҚ Tomimasa|qq=}}, the shrine was renamed from "SannЕҚ Daigongen Palace" to "Susuki Mizu Shrine" by the {{ill|Yoshida clan|ja|еҗүз”°е®¶|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshida clan|qq=}} in 1781 ({{ill|Tenmei|ja|еӨ©жҳҺ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenmei|qq=}} 1). The shrine formerly held rituals involving the exchange of {{ill|Mikoshi|ja|зҘһијҝ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mikoshi|qq=}} with {{ill|Amamiya Shrine|ja|йӣЁе®®гҒ®еқҗж—ҘеҗүзҘһзӨҫ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amamiya Shrine|qq=}} but discontinued this in 1872 (Meiji 5).

The shrine grounds span approximately 27 ken (east to west) and 34 ken (north to south). Revered as a {{ill|Water deity|ja|ж°ҙзҘһ|1=Suijin|lt=water god|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Water deity|13=User:Immanuelle/Suijin|qq=}}, it has long served as the guardian deity of the Yashiro Irrigation Weir.

