'''Susuki Mizu Shrine''' (й Ҳй ҲеІҗж°ҙзҘһзӨҫ) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|зҘһзӨҫ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto shrine|qq=}} located in {{ill|Chikuma, Nagano|ja|еҚғжӣІеёӮ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chikuma, Nagano|qq=}}, {{ill|Nagano Prefecture|ja|й•·йҮҺзңҢ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nagano Prefecture|qq=}}, Japan. It is associated with the ancient {{ill|Shrines listed in Engishiki|ja|ејҸеӨ–зӨҫ|1=Shikigeisha|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shrines listed in Engishiki|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikigeisha|qq=}} Susuki Mizu Shrine and held the status of a village shrine (ж—§йғ·зӨҫ) under the {{ill|Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|ja|иҝ‘д»ЈзӨҫж јеҲ¶еәҰ|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|1=Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|13=User:Immanuelle/Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|qq=}}.

== Overview ==
According to shrine tradition, Susuki Mizu Shrine was founded in the second year of the {{ill|HakuhЕҚ period|ja|зҷҪйіі|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/HakuhЕҚ period|qq=}} (673). Initially, it was known as the "HЕҚri Shrine" (зҘқзҘһзӨҫ), a name derived from the {{ill|Engishiki|ja|е»¶е–ңејҸ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Engishiki|qq=}}. During the {{ill|JЕҚgan (era)|ja|иІһиҰі|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/JЕҚgan (era)|qq=}} era, following flooding of the {{ill|Chikuma River|ja|еҚғжӣІе·қ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chikuma River|qq=}}, the regional governor of {{ill|Hanishina District|ja|еҹҙз§‘йғЎ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hanishina District|qq=}}, {{ill|Kanasashi no Masanaga|ja|йҮ‘еҲәжӯЈй•·|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanasashi no Masanaga|qq=}}, brought the {{ill|SannЕҚ Gongen|ja|еұұзҺӢжЁ©зҸҫ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/SannЕҚ Gongen|qq=}} from {{ill|Hie Shrine|ja|ж—ҘеҗүеӨ§зӨҫ|1=Hiyoshi Taisha|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hie Shrine|13=User:Immanuelle/Hiyoshi Taisha|qq=}} and enshrined it alongside the main deity.

In the Edo period, the shrine received the patronage of the {{ill|Sanada clan|ja|зңҹз”°ж°Ҹ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sanada clan|qq=}}, who donated 300 koku of land and additional resources for rituals. The shrine was reconstructed by {{ill|Tatekawa WashirЕҚ Tomimasa|ja|з«Ӣе·қе’ҢеӣӣйғҺеҜҢжҳҢ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tatekawa WashirЕҚ Tomimasa|qq=}} in the fourth year of {{ill|Kaei|ja|еҳүж°ё|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kaei|qq=}} (1851) following repeated flood damage. In the first year of {{ill|Tenmei|ja|еӨ©жҳҺ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenmei|qq=}} (1781), the shrine was renamed "Susuki Mizu Shrine" by the head of Shinto priests, the {{ill|Urabe clan|ja|еҚңйғЁж°Ҹ|en|draft:Yoshida family|simple|User:Immanuelle/Urabe_clan|fr|User:Immanuelle/Urabe_clan|lt=Yoshida clan|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Urabe clan|qq=}}.

Previously, the shrine participated in rituals involving the transfer of portable shrines (зҘһијҝ) with {{ill|Amamiya Shrine|ja|йӣЁе®®гҒ®еқҗж—ҘеҗүзҘһзӨҫ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amamiya Shrine|qq=}}, but these were discontinued in the fifth year of {{ill|Meiji|ja|жҳҺжІ»|1=Meiji era|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji era|qq=}} (1872).

The shrine site measures approximately 27 ken east-to-west and 34 ken north-to-south. It has been worshipped as a {{ill|water deity|ja|ж°ҙзҘһ|1=Suijin|lt=water god|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/water deity|13=User:Immanuelle/Suijin|qq=}}, serving as the guardian of the Yashiro irrigation system.

